      <data key="d4">Preamble</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OBL-0136">
      <data key="d2">obligation</data>
      <data key="d3">In jurisdictions that do not allow the use of external ratings for regulatory purposes, the following
supervisory haircuts (assuming daily mark-to-market, daily remargining and a 10-business day holding
period), expressed as percentages, must be used to determine the haircuts appropriate to the collateral
(Hc) and to the exposure (He):
73 Includes: PSEs that are treated as sovereigns by the national supervisor, as well as multilateral development banks receiving a
0% risk weight.</data>
      <data key="d4">Preamble</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OBL-0137">
      <data key="d2">obligation</data>
      <data key="d3">For SFTs in which the bank lends, or posts as collateral, non-eligible instruments, the haircut to
be applied on the exposure must be 30%.</data>
      <data key="d4">Preamble</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OBL-0138">
      <data key="d2">obligation</data>
      <data key="d3">Where the collateral is a basket of assets, the haircut on the basket must be H =∑ aH , where
i i i
a is the weight of the asset (as measured by units of currency) in the basket and H the haircut applicable
i i
to that asset.</data>
      <data key="d4">Preamble</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OBL-0139">
      <data key="d2">obligation</data>
      <data key="d3">For some transactions, depending on the nature and frequency of the revaluation and
remargining provisions, different holding periods and thus different haircuts must be applied.</data>
      <data key="d4">Preamble</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OBL-0140">
      <data key="d2">obligation</data>
      <data key="d3">Where a bank has a transaction or netting set that meets the criteria outlined in paragraphs 41(i)
or 41(ii) of the counterparty credit risk standards, the minimum holding period must be the margin period
of risk that would apply under those paragraphs.</data>
      <data key="d4">Preamble</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OBL-0141">
      <data key="d2">obligation</data>
      <data key="d3">When the frequency of remargining or revaluation is longer than the minimum, the minimum
haircut numbers must be scaled up depending on the actual number of business days between
remargining or revaluation.</data>
      <data key="d4">Preamble</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OBL-0142">
      <data key="d2">obligation</data>
      <data key="d3">The 10-business day haircuts provided in paragraphs 163 and 164 are the
default haircuts and these haircuts must be scaled up or down using the formula below:
( )
N + T −1
H =H R M
10 10
where:
H = haircut
H 10 = 10-business day haircut for instrument
N R = actual number of business days between remargining for capital market transactions or
revaluation for secured transactions
T M = minimum holding period for the type of transaction.</data>
      <data key="d4">Preamble</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OBL-0143">
      <data key="d2">obligation</data>
      <data key="d3">In addition, netting agreements must:
Basel III: Finalising post-crisis reforms 43
(a) provide the non-defaulting party the right to terminate and close out in a timely manner all
transactions under the agreement upon an event of default, including in the event of insolvency
or bankruptcy of the counterparty;</data>
      <data key="d4">Preamble</data>
      <data key="d5">provide the non-defaulting party the right to terminate and close out in a timely manner all transactions under the agreement upon an event of default</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUBJ:netting agreements">
      <data key="d2">subject</data>
      <data key="d6">netting agreements</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COND:OBL-0143">
      <data key="d2">condition</data>
      <data key="d6">including in the event of insolvency or bankruptcy of the counterparty</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OBL-0144">
      <data key="d2">obligation</data>
      <data key="d3">Banks using standard supervisory haircuts for repo-style transactions conducted under a master
netting agreement must use the following formula to calculate their exposure amount:
