      <data key="d4">Preamble</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OBL-0145">
      <data key="d2">obligation</data>
      <data key="d3">The requirements are not applicable to banks in jurisdictions that are prohibited from
conducting such transactions below the minimum haircut floors specified in paragraph 184 below.</data>
      <data key="d4">Preamble</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OBL-0146">
      <data key="d2">obligation</data>
      <data key="d3">For these transactions, the floors must be calculated according to the
formula set out in paragraph 187.</data>
      <data key="d4">Preamble</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OBL-0147">
      <data key="d2">obligation</data>
      <data key="d3">In-scope SFTs which do not meet the haircut floors must be treated as unsecured loans to the
counterparties.</data>
      <data key="d4">Preamble</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OBL-0148">
      <data key="d2">obligation</data>
      <data key="d3">To determine whether the treatment in paragraph 185 applies to an in-scope SFT (or a netting
set of SFTs in the case of portfolio-level haircuts), we must compare the collateral haircut H (real or
calculated as per the rules below) and a haircut floor f (from paragraph 184 above or calculated as per the
below rules).</data>
      <data key="d4">Preamble</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OBL-0149">
      <data key="d2">obligation</data>
      <data key="d3">• For a single collateral-for-collateral SFT, lending collateral A and receiving collateral B, the H is
still be defined by the amount of collateral received but the effective floor of the transaction must
integrate the floor of the two types of collateral and can be computed as:
 1   1  1+f
f =   −1= B −1
